ry and helps erase the artificial distinctions between prehistory and history.Contributions to the volume offer significant new interpretations of primary data as well as reconsidering classic ethnographic material. Beyond Kinship crosses the boundaries within anthropology—not only between cultural anthropology and archaeology but between structural—symbolic and materialist approaches and between American and British schools of anthropology; it is intended to advance the fruitful dialogue now taking place within the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDwellings. 0aKinship. 0aMaterial cultur. 0aVernacular architecture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.1 aCunningham, Clark E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillespie, Susan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillespie, Susan D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJoyce, Rosemary A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoyce, Rosemary A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKirch, Patrick V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKinnon, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSandstrom, Alan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTringham, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaterson, Roxana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151282162840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512821628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781512821628.jpg  aEB